# BuildY — Catalog Blocks

Use this rule only when the user asks to add or refine a **Catalog** block or
component under `internal/ui/blocks/`.

Catalog work is separate from the BuildY runtime app. Runtime screens continue
to render through `internal/ui/layout`, `internal/views`, `internal/site`, and
`internal/fixtures`. Catalog packages are isolated shadcn-like examples that may
duplicate runtime layout ideas such as sidebars, headers, cards, or page shells.

## Purpose

Catalog blocks are accumulated in BuildY first. Later, after enough stable
examples exist, selected packages may move to the shared UI registry. Do not
design for CLI/CDN registry automation yet.

## Isolation Contract

A Catalog block must be copyable as a folder into `@Templ/examples` and work with
the simple preview server there.

The copied block must not depend on:

- BuildY `internal/views`;
- BuildY `internal/site`;
- BuildY `internal/fixtures`;
- BuildY runtime `internal/ui/layout`;
- product routes, handlers, storage, or generated app state.

Allowed dependencies:

- `github.com/fastygo/templ/ui`;
- `github.com/fastygo/templ/components`;
- `github.com/fastygo/templ/utils`;
- files inside the same Catalog block folder;
- small local helpers included in the copied block folder.

## Package Shape

Prefer a self-contained folder:

```text
internal/ui/blocks/<group>/<block>/
  page.templ          # complete preview/page scaffold when needed
  props.go            # public props and small value types
  defaults.go         # English default data
  components/         # block-private nested components
  <block>.spec.md     # optional LLM/registry contract
  *_test.go           # optional render smoke test
```

Use page-level blocks when the example is a full shadcn-like screen. Nested
components may duplicate runtime pieces such as sidebars or headers because they
belong to the portable Catalog example, not to the BuildY app shell.

## Data Rules

- Defaults must live in the block folder, either in Go files or adjacent data
  files copied with the block.
- Default copy is always English.
- Do not read app locale JSON or BuildY fixtures from Catalog code.
- Keep blocks dumb: props in, markup out. No fetch, no database, no route logic.

## ARIA And Interaction Markup

Catalog blocks must prepare static ARIA and `data-ui8kit-*` attributes when they
include interactive surfaces such as mobile sheets, dialogs, dropdowns, tabs, or
accordions.

- The block owns the markup contract: trigger, panel, close controls, overlay,
  `aria-label`, `aria-labelledby`, `aria-controls`, `aria-expanded`, and
  `data-ui8kit-*` hooks.
- The host app or examples server owns the JavaScript bundle that registers the
  matching `@ui8kit/aria` pattern.
- Do not add custom JavaScript to Catalog blocks.
- Keep interaction IDs local to the block folder to avoid collisions when
  multiple Catalog blocks are rendered on the same examples page.

## Verification

Before considering a Catalog block complete, it should be possible to copy its
folder into `@Templ/examples`, import it from the demo page, and run:

```bash
cd @Templ/examples
bun run dev
```

The block should compile and render with the example server using only its copied
files plus `github.com/fastygo/templ`.

## Boundaries

- Do not wire Catalog blocks into BuildY runtime views unless the user explicitly
  asks for a prototype experiment.
- Do not update BuildY product fixtures just to support Catalog defaults.
- Do not introduce registry manifests, CDN publishing, or CLI commands in this
  phase.
- Keep names and folders registry-friendly, but prioritize local copyability and
  clean contracts over automation.
